{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492694"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:41:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:41:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1133"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1133"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.2,0.06,0.16,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1133"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28830"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"},{"type":"tags","id":"2133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4111"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39757"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man is admitted for a laparoscopic hiatal hernia repair and fundoplication. He has a medical history of chronic gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and a deep venous thrombosis after a tibial fracture four years ago. His medications include esomeprazole 40mg PO. He is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol. On examination, his vital signs are within normal limits and his BMI is 28kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. It is anticipated that he will be in hospital for only two days after the procedure. Mechanical calf compression devices will be used both during and after the surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enoxaparin 40mg until discharge","Enoxaparin 40mg for 10 days","Enoxaparin 40mg, followed by warfarin for three months (target INR 2-3)","Enoxaparin 40mg until discharge, followed by apixaban for three months","Enoxaparin 40mg until mobilising on ward"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis type of surgery is considered high risk for venous thromboembolism - it is an intra-abdominal procedure and will last longer than 45 minutes. The patient is also at increased risk of VTE as he suffered a previous DVT event and has an elevated BMI. Using the Caprini risk assessment:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAge = 1 point\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMajor surgery = 2 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious DVT = 3 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis Caprini score is 6, indicating a 1.8% chance of developing a VTE (high risk). Some other form of prophylaxis must be used in addition to the perioperative mechanical devices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current guidelines suggest a low molecular weight heparin which should be administered for between 7 and 10 days following surgery. However, \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin 40mg until mobilising\u003C/strong\u003E on the ward might be appropriate if he was a younger patient, without a history of VTE. In this case however, the risk factors warrant more extended chemoprophylaxis. As such, the current guidelines recommend \u0027Treat for 5 to 10 days or until mobility has returned to an anticipated or clinically acceptable level or when the patient is discharged from hospital.\u0027 In this particular scenario the patient should be kept on \u003Cstrong\u003Echemoprophylaxis (eg. enoxaparin) for between 5 and 10 days\u003C/strong\u003E post operatively and the exact time will depend on his degree of mobility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin 40mg until discharge \u003C/strong\u003Emight be appropriate if the patient did not have any additional risk factors for VTE aside from his surgery, however in this case, a slightly longer period of VTE prophylaxis is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient does not require \u003Cstrong\u003Eextended anticoagulation with an oral agent such as warfarin or apixaban, \u003C/strong\u003Eas he does not have a current venous thromboembolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chemoprophylaxis may need to be extended after a patient is discharged from hospital, depending on the type of surgery and the risk group of the patient."],"references":["Guideline for the Prevention of Venous Thromboembolism (VTE) in Adult Hospitalised Patients. In Queensland Health [online]. 2018. Available at: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0031/812938/vte-prevention-guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1133"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-28T20:41:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T21:29:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1133"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"r